The hibernate mapping for confluence content entity objects currently uses [batch fetching|http://www.hibernate.org/hib_docs/reference/en/html/performance.html] to get child pages.  

{code:xml|excerpt from ContentEntityObject.hbm.xml}
...
<bag name="children" lazy="true" inverse="true" cascade="none" batch-size="10">
...
{code}

This means that whenever the children of a page are queried, hibernate may choose to find children of other pages at the save time, to decreases the number of queries performed.

If there are three pages with uninitialised children in the session, then instead of selecting one pages children:

{code:sql|title=select one page's children}
select child.contentid, child.parentid ...
from content child ...
where child.parentid = ?
{code}

{code:sql|title=select three pages' children}
select child.contentid, child.parentid ...
from content child ...
where child.parentid = ? or child.parentid = ? or child.parentid = ?
{code} 

A customer has reported that the more complex query is running extremely slowly on DB2.  In fact, from their provided data, looking up 3 pages' children using the complex query takes 10 times as much DB CPU time than looking up a single page's children.

We should look into whether this "optimization" is actually a performance win anywhere and reassess the parameter.

h3. The Workaround.

The workaround is to change the "batch-size" parameter of the "chidren" relationship of the "PAGE" subclass from *10* to *1*.  This is in the classes/com/atlassian/confluence/core/ContentEntityObject.hbm.xml file.

Any customers who find that this query is particularly slow on their database should try the workaround.

